## 21. Password Hashing with bcrypt 🔐

**Never store plain text passwords!**

```bash
npm install bcrypt
```

```js
const bcrypt = require('bcrypt')

// When saving a user — hash the password first
router.post('/', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const hashedPassword = await bcrypt.hash(req.body.password, 10)
    // 10 = salt rounds (complexity of hashing)

    const user = new User({
      name: req.body.name,
      email: req.body.email,
      password: hashedPassword  // save hash, not plain text!
    })
    await user.save()
    res.status(201).json({ message: "User saved!", user })
  } catch (err) {
    res.status(400).json({ error: err.message })
  }
})
```

**How hashing works:**
```
Register: "123456" → bcrypt.hash() → "$2b$10$9Y94..." (saved in DB)
Login:    "123456" → bcrypt.hash() → compared with stored hash
                                      match = login success ✅
```

You can never reverse `"$2b$10$9Y94..."` back to `"123456"` — that's what makes it safe!

