## 25. Controllers + Middleware Organization

Use controllers to keep route files small and focused on endpoints. Controllers hold the actual database logic.

**routes/users.js:**
```js
const express = require('express')
const router = express.Router()
const authMiddleware = require('../middleware/authMiddleware')
const { getAllUsers, saveusers } = require('../controllers/userController')

router.get('/', authMiddleware, getAllUsers)
router.post('/', saveusers)
module.exports = router
```

**controllers/userController.js:**
```js
const User = require('../models/User')

const getAllUsers = async (req, res) => {
  const users = await User.find().select('-password')
  res.json(users)
}
```

This pattern helps with:
- testing logic separately
- reusing code across routes
- keeping routes readable

